1
00:00:00,960 --> 00:00:10,120
Ada and Zangemann: a tale of software, skateboards, and raspberry ice cream.

2
00:00:10,120 --> 00:00:14,680
Once upon a time, there was a little girl named Ada.

3
00:00:14,680 --> 00:00:19,920
Her family was so poor that all their savings fit inside a cookie jar.

4
00:00:19,920 --> 00:00:24,520
They didn't have enough money to live in a proper home.

5
00:00:24,520 --> 00:00:31,700
Instead, Ada lived with her mother and her little brother, Alan, in a cabin near a junkyard

6
00:00:31,700 --> 00:00:36,040
on the edge of town.

7
00:00:36,040 --> 00:00:42,580
Far away at the other end of town lived a famous inventor named Zangemann.

8
00:00:42,580 --> 00:00:45,740
He was immensely rich.

9
00:00:45,740 --> 00:00:50,760
No sheet of paper in the world was big enough to show his bank balance with all its numbers

10
00:00:50,760 --> 00:00:54,180
and zeros.

11
00:00:54,180 --> 00:01:00,060
He lived in a huge house with a swimming pool and waterslide, lots of staircases and

12
00:01:00,060 --> 00:01:09,960
towers, hundreds of windows, and so many rooms that he often got lost in them himself.

13
00:01:09,960 --> 00:01:13,660
Zangemann's mansion stood high on a hill.

14
00:01:13,660 --> 00:01:18,340
From there, he could look out over the whole city.

15
00:01:18,340 --> 00:01:21,980
Computers had fascinated Zangemann ever since he was a child.

16
00:01:21,980 --> 00:01:23,840
When he was young, computers were huge machines.

17
00:01:23,840 --> 00:01:28,080
with lots of cables and loud noisy fans.

18
00:01:28,080 --> 00:01:34,780
At school, little Zangemann often dreamed of all the things he would do with computers

19
00:01:34,780 --> 00:01:37,780
if they were just a little bit smaller.

20
00:01:37,780 --> 00:01:42,060
Small enough that they could be built into other fun things.

21
00:01:42,060 --> 00:01:43,520
He knew what he would do.

22
00:01:43,520 --> 00:01:48,220
First, he would build a computer into his skateboard so that it would make cool noises

23
00:01:48,220 --> 00:01:49,600
when he rode it.

24
00:01:49,600 --> 00:01:53,500
Maybe a fire engine siren or the sound of a rocket launch.

25
00:01:53,500 --> 00:01:58,500
Then he would use a computer to invent ice cream making machines.

26
00:01:58,500 --> 00:02:03,000
The computer would mix the coolest flavors and even sell the ice cream.

27
00:02:03,000 --> 00:02:08,140
There would be machines on every street corner, and he could get ice cream in his favorite

28
00:02:08,140 --> 00:02:13,200
flavor whenever he felt like it, and just as much as he wanted.

29
00:02:13,200 --> 00:02:18,020
After that, he’d build a cleaning robot and a block sorting machine so that his room would

30
00:02:18,020 --> 00:02:21,760
always be neat and clean.

31
00:02:21,760 --> 00:02:23,160
Zangemann had great new ideas.

32
00:02:23,160 --> 00:02:25,200
like these every day.

33
00:02:25,200 --> 00:02:28,680
He could think of nothing else.

34
00:02:28,680 --> 00:02:34,200
As the years went by, Zangemann grew bigger and computers got smaller.

35
00:02:34,200 --> 00:02:41,620
In fact, by the time he finished school, they were so small they fit into his pocket.

36
00:02:41,620 --> 00:02:46,280
The smallest ones even fit on his fingertip.

37
00:02:46,280 --> 00:02:52,820
“Finally, I can turn all my ideas into real things”,

38
00:02:52,820 --> 00:02:54,200
Zangemann exclaimed.

39
00:02:54,200 --> 00:02:55,940
And he got right to work.

40
00:02:55,940 --> 00:03:00,700
He found ways to put the small computers into all kinds of things to make them even more

41
00:03:00,700 --> 00:03:02,920
fun and useful.

42
00:03:02,920 --> 00:03:04,400
And then he sold them.

43
00:03:04,400 --> 00:03:08,020
Adults and children loved his inventions.

44
00:03:08,020 --> 00:03:13,060
All the kids wanted to have one of his skateboards, complete with the latest sounds to show off

45
00:03:13,060 --> 00:03:17,220
to their friends at school.

46
00:03:17,220 --> 00:03:21,980
Kids also loved his speaker invention, which could instantly play any song you requested.

47
00:03:21,980 --> 00:03:30,080
And of course, everyone loved the ice cream served every afternoon from the automatic,

48
00:03:30,080 --> 00:03:35,680
extra delicious, original Zangemann ice cream machine.

49
00:03:35,680 --> 00:03:39,220
It all seemed like magic, but the secret was simple.

50
00:03:39,220 --> 00:03:44,740
The little computers that Zangemann built into his machines made it all possible.

51
00:03:44,740 --> 00:03:48,100
These inventions were very popular at Ada's school.

52
00:03:48,100 --> 00:03:51,640
And many of her friends rode around on the cool skateboards.

53
00:03:51,640 --> 00:03:57,780
Ada was often sad, since her mother couldn't buy her any of those great things.

54
00:03:57,780 --> 00:03:59,380
No skateboard.

55
00:03:59,380 --> 00:04:00,960
No speakers.

56
00:04:00,960 --> 00:04:02,080
No ice cream.

57
00:04:02,080 --> 00:04:05,520
Luckily, Ada lived right next to the junkyard.

58
00:04:05,520 --> 00:04:09,700
There were lots of broken gadgets and rusty parts, which she put together to make cool

59
00:04:09,700 --> 00:04:11,680
new things.

60
00:04:11,680 --> 00:04:16,460
Like a soapbox she and Alan rode roaring down the hill.

61
00:04:16,460 --> 00:04:17,800
A windmill.

62
00:04:17,800 --> 00:04:21,300
And scary junk monsters, which she and Alan would fight together.

63
00:04:21,300 --> 00:04:25,840
She also found many useful items.

64
00:04:25,840 --> 00:04:28,680
An old cell phone, for example.

65
00:04:28,680 --> 00:04:32,320
The screen was cracked, but she could fix that.

66
00:04:32,320 --> 00:04:38,240
And while there wasn’t internet at the junkyard, she could get access somewhere else.

67
00:04:38,240 --> 00:04:43,400
Ada had so much fun tinkering in the junkyard, and fixing broken things, that she forgot

68
00:04:43,400 --> 00:04:47,960
all about the skateboards and the ice cream.

69
00:04:47,960 --> 00:04:50,300
Because everyone bought his inventions,

70
00:04:50,300 --> 00:04:51,260
Zangemann soon became

71
00:04:51,260 --> 00:04:54,260
the richest person in the whole world.

72
00:04:54,260 --> 00:04:59,840
With all his money, he bought a huge golden computer with a keyboard made of jewels and

73
00:04:59,840 --> 00:05:05,460
set it up in the largest room of his mansion.

74
00:05:05,460 --> 00:05:12,780
From there, over the internet, he could control all the little computers built into his inventions.

75
00:05:12,780 --> 00:05:17,260
All he had to do was press the proper key on the golden computer,

76
00:05:17,260 --> 00:05:21,220
and immediately all the ice cream machines in town would dispense.

77
00:05:21,220 --> 00:05:23,220
only vanilla ice cream.

78
00:05:23,220 --> 00:05:30,220
If Zangemann wanted people to eat chocolate ice cream, he pressed the key for chocolate ice cream.

79
00:05:30,220 --> 00:05:35,220
If he gave the order for lemon ice cream, the machines made only lemon ice cream.

80
00:05:35,220 --> 00:05:45,220
Zangemann loved his inventions and was always thrilled at how amazingly well his machines worked.

81
00:05:45,220 --> 00:05:49,220
Sometimes, people were disappointed when their favorite flavor wasn't available.

82
00:05:49,220 --> 00:05:50,220
But what could they do?

83
00:05:50,220 --> 00:05:55,220
After all, there was ice cream on every street corner.

84
00:05:55,220 --> 00:06:02,220
Zangemann had a lot of fun pressing the sparkling keys and watching people eat ice cream.

85
00:06:02,220 --> 00:06:08,220
He spent many hours every day in front of his golden computer doing this.

86
00:06:08,220 --> 00:06:15,220
Again and again, he looked down on the city through a long telescope,

87
00:06:15,220 --> 00:06:19,220
observing how reliably his inventions carried out his commands.

88
00:06:19,220 --> 00:06:31,220
When he wasn't sitting at his golden computer, Zangemann was building his little computers into new devices and then selling those.

89
00:06:31,220 --> 00:06:36,220
He built washing machines that sent a message to your cell phone when your laundry was done.

90
00:06:36,220 --> 00:06:41,220
He made vacuums that played happy music instead of droning loudly.

91
00:06:41,220 --> 00:06:45,220
He invented light bulbs that turned on and off at the snap of a finger

92
00:06:45,220 --> 00:06:48,220
and cars that told you where the nearest grocery store was.

93
00:06:48,220 --> 00:06:55,220
Soon, almost every appliance in the world had a Zangemann computer built into it.

94
00:06:55,220 --> 00:07:02,220
Not all of his inventions seemed necessary at first, but people bought everything he made.

95
00:07:02,220 --> 00:07:05,220
That's just the way it was.

96
00:07:05,220 --> 00:07:10,220
Everyone wanted the devices made by Zangemann, the greatest inventor in the world.

97
00:07:10,220 --> 00:07:17,220
One day, Zangemann thought, "Today, I want to see my inventions up close."

98
00:07:17,220 --> 00:07:24,220
He put away his big telescope, then climbed down the many stairs of his mansion.

99
00:07:24,220 --> 00:07:30,220
And ventured out into the city, full of anticipation at the thought of enjoying his cool devices.

100
00:07:30,220 --> 00:07:35,220
“Maybe a little trip might even give me a few new ideas.

101
00:07:35,220 --> 00:07:42,220
If I'm completely honest, my last inventions weren't quite as useful as the first ones…”, Zangemann pondered.

102
00:07:42,220 --> 00:07:46,220
“But my ice cream machines are and will remain

103
00:07:46,220 --> 00:07:50,220
second to none,” he thought immediately afterward.,

104
00:07:50,220 --> 00:07:57,220
and not without pride, as he passed a group of people all eating coconut ice cream, the flavor of the day.

105
00:07:57,220 --> 00:08:03,220
He was completely absorbed in his thoughts, when suddenly, BAM!

106
00:08:03,220 --> 00:08:06,220
Something crashed into his shin.

107
00:08:06,220 --> 00:08:10,220
Zangemann yelped and looked around for the cause.

108
00:08:10,220 --> 00:08:15,220
A startled child stood in front of him, holding an original Zangemann skateboard under his arm.

109
00:08:15,220 --> 00:08:22,220
"S-sorry, I didn't mean to do that," the child stammered.

110
00:08:22,220 --> 00:08:24,220
But Zangemann wasn't listening.

111
00:08:24,220 --> 00:08:27,220
An angry Zangemann limped away.

112
00:08:27,220 --> 00:08:30,220
Suddenly, he heard loud music.

113
00:08:30,220 --> 00:08:34,220
He had never before heard something so horrible.

114
00:08:34,220 --> 00:08:41,220
He looked around and saw that the music was coming from a loudspeaker he himself had constructed.

115
00:08:41,220 --> 00:08:44,220
A child across the street was holding it.

116
00:08:44,220 --> 00:08:49,220
The child seemed to like the music.

117
00:08:49,220 --> 00:08:53,220
But it gave Zangemann a terrible headache.

118
00:08:53,220 --> 00:08:57,220
And his mood worsened.

119
00:08:57,220 --> 00:09:02,220
This was not how he had imagined his walk.

120
00:09:02,220 --> 00:09:06,220
Zangemann was so furious with the two children.

121
00:09:06,220 --> 00:09:10,220
How dare they use his inventions this way?

122
00:09:10,220 --> 00:09:13,220
That night, he couldn't sleep.

123
00:09:13,220 --> 00:09:17,220
So he sat down at his golden computer.

124
00:09:17,220 --> 00:09:21,220
From there, he gave all the little computers in the skateboards a command

125
00:09:21,220 --> 00:09:25,220
that they were no longer allowed to go on sidewalks.

126
00:09:25,220 --> 00:09:30,220
He ordered the small computers in the speakers to play music only at a low volume,

127
00:09:30,220 --> 00:09:32,220
except for his favorite music,

128
00:09:32,220 --> 00:09:38,220
which he immediately turned on to get into a better mood.

129
00:09:38,220 --> 00:09:42,220
The next day, there was a big commotion at Ada's school.

130
00:09:42,220 --> 00:09:46,220
On the way to school, the kids' skateboards had stopped working.

131
00:09:46,220 --> 00:09:49,220
The wheels simply stood still.

132
00:09:49,220 --> 00:09:53,220
And the children could no longer turn up the volume on their speakers.

133
00:09:53,220 --> 00:09:55,220
What was going on?

134
00:09:55,220 --> 00:09:59,220
Although she didn't own any of these things,

135
00:09:59,220 --> 00:10:05,220
Ada wondered why the skateboards and the speakers suddenly stopped working.

136
00:10:05,220 --> 00:10:07,220
But she didn't really have time to think much about it,

137
00:10:07,220 --> 00:10:10,220
because she was tinkering again.

138
00:10:10,220 --> 00:10:15,220
She put together a complete bicycle from the parts of three broken bicycles.

139
00:10:15,220 --> 00:10:18,220
She gave the bicycle to her mother as a present

140
00:10:18,220 --> 00:10:22,220
so that she wouldn't have to spend her money on bus tickets to work.

141
00:10:22,220 --> 00:10:25,220
For her brother, Ada built a loudspeaker

142
00:10:25,220 --> 00:10:28,220
so he could fall asleep to nice stories in the evenings

143
00:10:28,220 --> 00:10:32,220
when their mother was still at work.

144
00:10:32,220 --> 00:10:36,220
After a few days, the initial shock at Ada's school was forgotten.

145
00:10:36,220 --> 00:10:39,220
The skateboards still didn't go on the sidewalk.

146
00:10:39,220 --> 00:10:42,220
But apart from that, they still worked.

147
00:10:42,220 --> 00:10:46,220
And so now the children rode in circles around the playground

148
00:10:46,220 --> 00:10:49,220
and listened to soft music.

149
00:10:49,220 --> 00:10:56,220
Only a strange, pompous marching music continued to play at an unchanged volume,

150
00:10:56,220 --> 00:11:00,220
which the children found rather puzzling.

151
00:11:00,220 --> 00:11:02,220
Ada loved Wednesdays.

152
00:11:02,220 --> 00:11:06,220
Every Wednesday, her mother and Alan would pick her up from school,

153
00:11:06,220 --> 00:11:08,220
and they would all go to the library together.

154
00:11:08,220 --> 00:11:12,220
Ada was always drawn to the technology section.

155
00:11:12,220 --> 00:11:16,220
There were books with blueprints, instructions for experiments,

156
00:11:16,220 --> 00:11:21,220
and explanations of how different devices worked.

157
00:11:21,220 --> 00:11:26,220
In the library, Ada could also go online with her cell phone.

158
00:11:26,220 --> 00:11:31,220
She quickly realized that there was also much to discover on the Internet.

159
00:11:31,220 --> 00:11:37,220
There, many people shared their ideas and prepared tips to help others.

160
00:11:37,220 --> 00:11:42,220
On one of those afternoons, Ada learned two new words:

161
00:11:42,220 --> 00:11:47,220
hardware and software.

162
00:11:47,220 --> 00:11:51,220
Hardware was a word for something Ada already knew:

163
00:11:51,220 --> 00:11:55,220
the electronic devices she tinkered with after school,

164
00:11:55,220 --> 00:11:58,220
or those devices she could hold in her hands and try to fix

165
00:11:58,220 --> 00:12:01,220
or make into something else.

166
00:12:01,220 --> 00:12:06,220
What was completely new to Ada was the word software.

167
00:12:06,220 --> 00:12:09,220
She soon learned that it meant instructions that ran on a computer

168
00:12:09,220 --> 00:12:13,220
to control other devices or computers.

169
00:12:13,220 --> 00:12:19,220
Some books called those instructions "programs" or "code."

170
00:12:19,220 --> 00:12:23,220
With such a computer program, one could, for example,

171
00:12:23,220 --> 00:12:29,220
tell a loudspeaker which song to play and how loud.

172
00:12:29,220 --> 00:12:32,220
The best thing about Ada's new discovery was realizing

173
00:12:32,220 --> 00:12:35,220
she could tinker with software just as she could with hardware.

174
00:12:35,220 --> 00:12:40,220
Hardware is built with tools:

175
00:12:40,220 --> 00:12:44,220
hammers, drills, and screws.

176
00:12:44,220 --> 00:12:48,220
Software is built simply by writing down the commands for the hardware,

177
00:12:48,220 --> 00:12:50,220
one after the other.

178
00:12:50,220 --> 00:12:53,220
There was a separate language for this:

179
00:12:53,220 --> 00:12:56,220
the programming language.

180
00:12:56,220 --> 00:13:01,220
With software, Ada could make her inventions even more useful.

181
00:13:01,220 --> 00:13:04,220
She really wanted to learn the programming language.

182
00:13:04,220 --> 00:13:11,220
Over the next few weeks, Ada spent her afternoons in a library.

183
00:13:11,220 --> 00:13:17,220
She found books and websites that explained how programming languages and code worked.

184
00:13:17,220 --> 00:13:22,220
For Ada, it felt a bit like learning a secret language,

185
00:13:22,220 --> 00:13:25,220
or like studying vocabulary in the school.

186
00:13:25,220 --> 00:13:28,220
Ada ate it all up.

187
00:13:28,220 --> 00:13:32,220
She expected her first program to do something simple:

188
00:13:32,220 --> 00:13:35,220
make this lamp blink.

189
00:13:35,220 --> 00:13:38,220
Of course, she wanted to try her program out right away

190
00:13:38,220 --> 00:13:41,220
to see if it really worked.

191
00:13:41,220 --> 00:13:46,220
At the junkyard, she connected her cell phone to a small LED lamp.

192
00:13:46,220 --> 00:13:50,220
Then she typed the lines of code into her cell phone.

193
00:13:50,220 --> 00:13:52,220
At first, nothing happened.

194
00:13:52,220 --> 00:13:55,220
Ada wondered where the error could be.

195
00:13:55,220 --> 00:13:58,220
She made a few small changes and tried again and...

196
00:13:58,220 --> 00:14:00,220
Yes!

197
00:14:00,220 --> 00:14:03,220
The little light began to flash.

198
00:14:03,220 --> 00:14:08,220
On, off, on, off.

199
00:14:08,220 --> 00:14:12,220
Ada looked at the LED in amazement.

200
00:14:12,220 --> 00:14:15,220
She had written her first program!

201
00:14:15,220 --> 00:14:18,220
Ada was totally thrilled.

202
00:14:18,220 --> 00:14:21,220
She imagined all the great things she could do.

203
00:14:21,220 --> 00:14:24,220
If she just entered the right code,

204
00:14:24,220 --> 00:14:27,220
she could make her inventions do exactly what she wanted.

205
00:14:27,220 --> 00:14:29,220
It was not so easy.

206
00:14:29,220 --> 00:14:34,220
But after a few weeks, Ada wrote a truly useful program.

207
00:14:34,220 --> 00:14:38,220
One that would make Alan's speakers automatically turn off

208
00:14:38,220 --> 00:14:41,220
half an hour after he had fallen asleep.

209
00:14:41,220 --> 00:14:47,220
Ada also had an idea for the next program she would write.

210
00:14:47,220 --> 00:14:49,220
It was a bigger deal.

211
00:14:49,220 --> 00:14:51,220
A real project.

212
00:14:51,220 --> 00:14:55,220
She would probably need the whole summer break for it.

213
00:14:55,220 --> 00:14:58,220
And she could hardly wait.

214
00:14:58,220 --> 00:15:06,220
Zangaemann had slept horribly every night since his terrible walk in the city.

215
00:15:06,220 --> 00:15:10,220
When he went to bed each night, worries plagued him.

216
00:15:10,220 --> 00:15:12,220
“Oh, no.

217
00:15:12,220 --> 00:15:14,220
My marvelous inventions.

218
00:15:14,220 --> 00:15:18,220
It can't be that everyone just plays around with them.

219
00:15:18,220 --> 00:15:21,220
All the things that could go wrong.

220
00:15:21,220 --> 00:15:25,220
I put so much thought into everything, down to the last detail.”

221
00:15:25,220 --> 00:15:27,220
Zangaemann pondered and pondered,

222
00:15:27,220 --> 00:15:31,220
and tossed and turned sleeplessly in his bed all night.

223
00:15:31,220 --> 00:15:37,220
Waking up one morning with a deeply furrowed brow,

224
00:15:37,220 --> 00:15:39,220
he made a decision.

225
00:15:39,220 --> 00:15:42,220
He needed to make a change.

226
00:15:42,220 --> 00:15:45,220
Zangaemann sat down at his computer

227
00:15:45,220 --> 00:15:48,220
and wrote one program after another.

228
00:15:48,220 --> 00:15:54,220
In these programs, he specified exactly what his inventions were to do

229
00:15:54,220 --> 00:15:56,220
and were not to do under any circumstances.

230
00:15:56,220 --> 00:16:00,220
The chaos had to stop.

231
00:16:00,220 --> 00:16:02,220
Once he was done,

232
00:16:02,220 --> 00:16:08,220
he sent all the new programs from his golden computer to people's devices.

233
00:16:08,220 --> 00:16:12,220
He ordered his speakers to play only his favorite music

234
00:16:12,220 --> 00:16:15,220
whenever he was within earshot.

235
00:16:15,220 --> 00:16:20,220
He programmed the ice cream machines to stop selling ice cream in the afternoon.

236
00:16:20,220 --> 00:16:25,220
After all, he didn't want his expensive clothes to get stained by ice cream

237
00:16:25,220 --> 00:16:27,220
while he was out for a walk.

238
00:16:27,220 --> 00:16:30,220
All day long, he sat at the computer

239
00:16:30,220 --> 00:16:35,220
and typed and typed and typed.

240
00:16:35,220 --> 00:16:38,220
Summer break was already halfway over.

241
00:16:38,220 --> 00:16:42,220
Ada stood in front of her big project and scratched her head.

242
00:16:42,220 --> 00:16:45,220
She had built a skateboard from old parts

243
00:16:45,220 --> 00:16:48,220
and then connected a motor to make the wheels turn.

244
00:16:48,220 --> 00:16:50,220
With a motorized skateboard,

245
00:16:50,220 --> 00:16:53,220
after school, Ada could zoom to the library

246
